A man is behind bars for illegal possession of lion bones
with R2.3 million. Captain Ndivhuwo Mulamu said Hawks, JMPD Dog unit and the
Department of Agriculture and Rural Development conducted a sting operation in
Krugersdorp which resulted to the apprehension of the suspect. "The investigation team received a tip off on Thursday
night, about a man who kept lion bones in his premises at Wentworth Park, near
Krugersdorp without valid permits," said Mulamu. He further stated that the team intercepted the premises and
discovered massive lion dried bones in the garage packaged in boxes and from the
clandestine laboratory inside bags ready for exportation to unknown
destination. "Further investigation also revealed that the suspectâ€™s
permit to possess lion bones and exportation has expired in 2016 and 2020
respectively," he said. He was immediately arrested and charged for contravening the
National Environmental Management-Biodiversity (NEMBA) Act," he added. Mulamu said the
suspect will appear at the Krugersdorp Magistrates Court for illegal possession
of lion bones on Monday, 01 March 2021.